<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>KING OF BEERS SEEKS BIGGER CROWN</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> It took several rounds and <b>talks behind the scenes</b> before Anheuser-Busch InBev, the worldâs largest brewer, and SABMiller agreed to form a beer behemoth,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/14/business/dealbook/anheuser-busch-inbev-sabmiller-beer-merger.html?ref=dealbook&#038;_r=0">Chad Bray and Michael J. de la Merced report in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Over the weekend, representatives from 3G Capital, the Brazilian investment firm that helped create Anheuser, held discussions with the Santo Domingo family, which owns 14 percent of SABMiller, according to people briefed on the matter. Having the Brazilians handle the negotiations with a fellow South American beer dynasty made sense, given the Santo Domingosâ are an investor in 3G. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">3G also negotiated with <b>SABMillerâs other big shareholder</b>, Altria, to secure its support. Altria, a tobacco giant, holds a 27 percent stake in SABMiller. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">By Sunday night, Alejandro Santo Domingo, the 38-year-old scion of his clan and one of the familyâs two representatives on the SABMiller board, had agreed to a price of 43.50 pounds, or $66.58, per share.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Having won over the family</b>, Carlos Brito, Anheuser-Busch InBevâs chief executive, and Olivier Goudet, the chairman, on Monday morning flew to London from New York to meet with Jan du Plessis, the SABMiller chairman.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They met at the unassuming brick offices of Robey Warshaw, the boutique investment bank that advises SABMiller. SABMiller wanted a <b>high premium for shareholders</b>, as well as assurances that Anheuser-Busch InBev would do what was necessary to receive regulatory approval. They agreed to a deal that evening. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In London trading on Tuesday, shares of SABMiller closed up more than 9 percent, at Â£39.48.<br />
The shares still traded about 10 percent below the Â£44 a share that Anheuser-Busch InBev finally agreed to pay because the deal faces <b>months of scrutiny from antitrust regulators</b>, <a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-10-13/sabmiller-trades-below-ab-inbev-bid-as-arbitragers-see-risk">Bloomberg News reports.</a> If a deal is expected to sail through, it typically trades just below the offer price, but traders are seeing better opportunities in other takeovers because the regulatory concerns might delay the deal. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The brewers may be forced to sell off some <b>assets in the United States and China</b>. As a combined entity they would control about 50 percent of global beer profits and 29 percent of sales. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Analysts expect the United States Justice Department to push for a break-up or sale of SABMillerâs <b>holdings in MillerCoors</b>, which owns brands like Miller Lite and Coors Light. The brewers face a hurdle in China, where SABMiller has a 49 percent stake in a joint venture that owns <b>Snow, Chinaâs best-selling beer brand</b>. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>SINK OR SWIM FOR MACRO HEDGE FUNDS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> It has been a difficult time to be making bets on big economic trends, but that hasnât stopped some <b>lesser-known macro funds</b> from thriving,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/14/business/dealbook/as-some-hedge-funds-sink-the-challenge-buoys-others.html?ref=dealbook">Alexandra Stevenson reports in DealBook.</a> Element Capital and Atreaus Capital have made double-digit gains for investors so far this year. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Across the hedge fund industry, <b>firms are shutting down</b> after months of market turmoil that has pulled under some of Wall Streetâs most well-versed traders. Bain Capital and Fortress liquidated their macro hedge funds. On Tuesday, the $27 billion Renaissance Technologies became the latest to tell investors that it would close a fund. Prominent investors like David Einhorn, William A. Ackman, Leon G. Cooperman and Daniel S. Loeb have had a reversal in gains made this year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many macro hedge funds have not been able to stem their losses in a year during which the Swiss central bank lifted its <b>cap on the Swiss franc</b> and the Chinese central bank decided to devalue its currency, the yuan. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But some of the losses have been <b>years in the making</b>. The Bain Capital Absolute Return Capital fund had been losing money for years, while Fortressâs flagship macro fund was down 1.6 percent last year. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Regardless, financial advisers are still recommending that investors <b>allocate more money to macro hedge funds</b>. SkyBridge Capital, a fund that invests in hedge funds, began the year with no money in any macro managers. Today it has more than 6 percent of its total $13.4 billion in assets under management in macro strategies.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Macro hedge funds have still managed to <b>outpace other hedge fund strategies</b>. Macro hedge funds have lost 0.6 percent so far this year, compared with 2.2 percent for the broader industry index and 2.7 percent for the Standard &#038; Poorâs 500-stock index.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>JPMORGANâS ROCKY THIRD QUARTER</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Itâs not just hedge funds feeling the toll of global markets. JPMorgan Chase, the nations largest bank by assets, said that revenue for all its major business lines <b>fell in the third quarter</b>, both year on year and compared with the last quarter. Overall revenue dropped 6 percent to $23.5 billion compared with the year before, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/14/business/dealbook/jpmorgan-chase-3q-earnings.html?ref=dealbook">Nathaniel Popper reports in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Although its profit was higher for the quarter, that was largely because of a <b>one-time $2.2 billion tax benefit</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Putting aside that benefit and other irregular items, the bank earned $5.4 billion, or $1.32 a share. When the one-time items were included, the bankâs profit rose 22 percent, to $6.8 billion, or $1.68 a share, in the third quarter.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The best-performing division was <b>the consumer bank</b>. Its overall revenue slipped, but it made more new loans, a sign of improvement in the United States economy. The better outlook for consumers allowed the bank to reduce the pool of money it has put aside to cover loan losses.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The biggest concerns for JPMorgan came from its <b>Wall Street operations</b>, which were already shrinking as a result of new regulations and uncertainty in the markets. Revenue from the bond and fixed-income trading desks, which have been bearing the brunt of the changes, fell 11 percent from a year earlier. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">JPMorganâs chief financial officer, Marianne Lake, blamed the volatile markets for the <b>struggles at JPMorganâs asset-management division</b>, which has been a steady outperformer in recent years. For the first time in several years, customer money flowed out of JPMorganâs various asset management products.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> <b>Wells Fargo</b> announces its third-quarter earnings at 8 a.m. The <b>Bank of America</b> earnings conference call starts at 8:30 a.m. The Bureau of Labor Statistics releases <b>producer prices</b> for September at 8:30 a.m. September <b>retail sales</b> data will be released at 8:30 a.m.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>TESTING A PLEDGE TO BALANCE SOCIAL MISSION WITH PROFIT</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Laureate Education, the worldâs largest for-profit higher education provider, is about to find out<br />
whether it can <b>scorn profits and still be embraced by Wall Street</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/14/business/dealbook/laureate-education-for-profit-school-public-benefit.html?ref=dealbook">Steven Davidoff Solomon writes in the Deal Professor column.</a><br />
It wants to become a public benefit company with a purpose of improving global education, not just its profits. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After being taken private in a $3.8 billion buyout led by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts in 2007, it is seeking to return to public markets.<br />
While it generates substantial cash, the company has lost about $227 million in the last two years because of high interest payments on its debt.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These losses and a volatile market already make its public offering <b>an uphill battle</b>. Thatâs why it is a bit odd that the company also announced that it would be the first publicly traded public benefit corporation, Mr. Solomon writes. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A public benefit corporation allows the companyâs board to <b>forgo profit in pursuit of a specific benefit</b> for society at large or the company. Laureateâs benefit is the âpositive effect for society and students by offering diverse education programs both online and at campuses around the globe.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The do-gooding may mask <b>deep, complicated issues</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It can be <b>hard to define a public benefit</b> and say exactly what âcreating a positive effectâ means. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âGiven the vagueness here, instead of being a force for good, Laureateâs benefit may simply result in greenwashing, that is, use of a public-relations-enhancing social purpose to <b>fritter away money without oversight</b>,â Mr. Solomon says. Vagueness might be acceptable in a private company with only a few owners, but Laureate will have thousands of shareholders. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Most people invest <b>through mutual funds</b>, which in many cases have an explicit fiduciary duty to invest for profit. So the question is whether many of the big institutions will avoid investing in Laureate because of its status.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In addition, there is the issue of governance.<br />
Laureate has a form of <b>governance that is especially unfriendly to shareholders</b> and raises questions about its public benefit status. Laureate will go public with dual-class stock, which will maintain K.K.R.âs control over the company. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">K.K.R. is out to sell its stake at the highest price possible, not benefit other causes, so this raises questions about <b>how much attention Laureate will pay to its status</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Companies today do many things that are not immediately profitable. They make donations and support causes all the time. So there is one final question: <b>What is this corporate form good for?</b></p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></div>
</div>
